RNA-seq Analysis of Bipolar II Disorder (HackBio NGS Internship 2025)

This project was completed as part of the HackBio NGS Internship 2025, focusing on RNA-seq transcriptomic profiling of iPSC-derived microglia from Bipolar II Disorder (BD-II) patients and healthy controls. The goal was to explore molecular differences between familial and sporadic BD-II using standard NGS and bioinformatics techniques.

#Skills Gained
 RNA-seq & NGS Processing
- FASTQ handling, adapter trimming, quality filtering
- Running FastQC, MultiQC, and interpreting quality reports
- Reference genome indexing & read alignment (STAR)
- Generating gene count matrices (featureCounts)

Bioinformatics & Computational Analysis
- Differential expression analysis (DESeq2)
- GO / KEGG functional enrichment
- Comparing shared vs unique gene signatures between conditions

Data Interpretation & Visualization
- Creating volcano plots, heatmaps, PCA plots
- Summarizing DEGs and pathway results
-Identifying immune, synaptic, and neurodevelopmental patterns

General Workflow Skills
- Working with SRA datasets
- Managing NGS pipelines in Linux
- Producing clear, reproducible analysis steps

#Dataset

Public RNA-seq dataset (SRA accessions SRR33243164â€“SRR33243171) consisting of BD-II and control microglia samples.

#Project Summary

Performed full RNA-seq workflow to identify transcriptional differences in familial vs sporadic BD-II, uncover dysregulated pathways, and evaluate biological relevance to psychiatric genomics.
